<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05020i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05020i">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05020i"> 20(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> forge document / (Macpherson&apos;s / Ossian)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">In order to prop up the Gospel story of the Crucifixion, the early Church <mark>forged</mark> certain Acts of Pilate, in which the Procurator of Judaea gives the Emperor Tiberius an account of the wonderful death, and still more wonderful resurrection, of Jesus Christ. Tertullian, writing in Africa in the early part of the third century, had the effrontery to cite <mark>this document</mark> as still preserved in the imperial archives. <small> G.W. Foote, <a name="BROM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#BROM"><cite title="source">Bible Romances</cite></a>, 4th ed. (1922) [The Crucifixion] 202</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c02022e" href="c02all.htm#c02022e">VI.C.02:022(e)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
